<a name='4ae4d988bc79e9addba4c4861d2667a0'></a><h2 style='background-color: #eeeeee; padding:10px'>Research Colloquium: Andruid Kerne&nbsp;&nbsp;<a href='#top'>[back to top]</a></h2>
<div style='margin:0 45px 0 45px'>
<p><strong>Date</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;May 3</p>

<p><strong>Location</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;UTA 5.522</p> 
<p><strong>Time</strong>:&nbsp;&nbsp;3:15-5:00 pm</p>
<p>Type of Talk: Weekly Research Colloquium<br />
<br />
Speaker/Affiliation: Andruid Kerne, Dept. of Computer Science, Texas A&M University<br />
<br />
Talk Title: Computing for Creativity and Cooperation<br />

<br />
Talk Abstract:<br />
<br />
The Interface Ecology Lab imagines and develops integral and sensitive human-centered computing to amplify individual and distributed cognition, supporting creativity and cooperation. Through iterative design, we develop the combinFormation information composition platform, games for teaching team coordination, embodied interaction modalities, methods for evaluation, and Support for Information Mapping in Programming Languages (S.IM.PL). The typical search interface is great for finding a single element of information, but weak for information discovery tasks, in which the human goal is to to develop ideas with support and stimulus from search. The combinFormation platform reconceptualizes information discovery support as mixed-initiative information composition, integrating browse-search-collect-and-organize, while representing each collection as a connected whole. To validate composition, information discovery metrics and grounded theory are extended and synthesized, developing formative and summative evaluation methodologies. Games for teaching team coordination connect firefighting practice, game mechanics, and wearable computing. Low cost non-mimetic simulation is found to engage participants in cooperation like firefighting. Embodied interaction involves the human in computing by engaging the senses as the physical world does. The S.IM.PL project develops new declarative mark-up languages integrated with extensions to imperative programming languages (e.g., Java, Objective C, ...), and communications frameworks, to assist developers traversing the divide between information and software.<br />
<br />
Speaker Bio:<br />
<br />
Andruid Kerne is Associate Professor of Computer Science and Engineering at Texas A&M University. He is director of the Interface Ecology Lab [http://ecologylab.net], addressing human-centered computing, digital media, creativity support tools, digital games, and education. Active National Science Foundation (NSF) awards are from the CAREER, Advanced Learning Technologies, and Intelligent Information Systems programs. His work has been presented by the Guggenheim Museum (New York), ACM CHI, SIGGRAPH, SIGIR, Multimedia, TEI, and Document Engineering, New York Digital Salon (New York, Spain, London, Beijing), ISEA (Paris, San Jose), the Ars Electronica Center (Linz), the Boston Cyber Arts Festival, and the Pan-African Theater Festival. Kerne holds a B.A. from Harvard in Applied Mathematics / Electronic Media, an M.A. in Music / Composition from Wesleyan, and a Ph.D. in Computer Science from NYU.</p>
</div>
